    <!-- PlaceHolder tag prevents inline radmenu.ClientID code below clashing with Utility.EnsureScriptManager(this); -->
    <script>

        $(document).ready(function () {
            giveAllMenuLinksAUniqueIdentifier();
            $(".rmLink").on("keydown", setSpacebarToOpenMenus);
        });

        function giveAllMenuLinksAUniqueIdentifier() {
            //Give all menu items a unique attribute value so that I can identify them when spacebar is clicked. Same 'menunumber' attribute is set in .aspx code on menu items.
            var index = 0;
            $(".telerik_main_menu li.rmItem a.rmLink").each(function (index) {
                $(this).attr("menunumber", index);
            });
        }

        function setSpacebarToOpenMenus(e) {
            //Open submenus on spacebar press. 
            var theKey = e.which;
            if (theKey == 32) { // 32 is keycode for spacebar. 
                var menuNumber = $(this).attr("menunumber");
                var menu = $find("ctl00_ContentPlaceHolder1_ctl01_radmenu");
                var menuItem = menu.findItemByAttribute("menunumber", menuNumber);
                var submenuItems = menuItem.get_items();
                if (submenuItems.get_count() > 0) {
                    if (menuItem.get_isOpen() == false) {
                        menuItem.open();
                        e.preventDefault();
                    };
                };
            };
        };

        function ClickItem(menu, args) {
            //Event set in OnClientItemClicking="ClickItem";
            //When user clicks (presses Enter key) a menu item, if submenu is not open, then open it; otherwise navigate to the item's link. 
            var item = args.get_item();
            var submenuItems = item.get_items();
            if (submenuItems.get_count() > 0) {
                //If submenu is closed, then open it; otherwise click the menu item link. 
                if (item.get_isOpen() == false) {
                    args.set_cancel(true); //Cancel the default click action so that it doesn't trigger the menu item's navigation link.
                    item.open();
                }
                else {
                    if (typeof item.redirectToLink == 'undefined') {
                        item.redirectToLink = true;
                        item.click();
                    } else {
                        delete item.redirectToLink;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

    </script>

role="main"><h1>Incoming Exchange Students</h1><div class="ptl_page"><div class="ptl_col_1"><div class="ptl_portlet_vertical"><div class="ptl_top_portlet" style="display:none;"></div><div id="ctl00_ContentPlaceHolder1_ctl07_divContent"><p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal"></strong><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">The University of Illinois at Chicago has established exchange partnerships with a number of universities around the world. Exchange programs give UIC students the chance to study at a university outside the United States and, in return, give a student at a partner university a chance to study at UIC. The information provided below is intended for incoming exchange students, or students at a partner university who would like to study at UIC. Outgoing exchange students, or UIC students who would like to study at a partner university outside the U.S. should consult the UIC Study Abroad Office website.<br>
<br>
</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);"></span></p>

    <li><a href="#ApplicationProcess">Application Process</a></li>

</ul>
<h2 id="ApplicationProcess">Application Process</h2>
<br>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">The application process for
incoming exchange students is a collaborative effort. Various UIC units are
involved including the Office of International Services, Academic
Departments, and UIC Admission. General questions about the application
process, however, can be directed to the Office of International Services at
<a href="mailto:ois@uic.edu">oisexchange@uic.edu</a>. <br>
<br>
</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);"></span>
</p>
<ul style="margin-top:0in" type="disc">
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Nomination</span>: </strong>To begin the
    application process, an authorized coordinator at the home institution
    must nominate the interested student(s) for the UIC Exchange Program through a <a href="/UserFiles/Servers/Server_1497/File/NominationFormFillable.pdf">nomination form</a>. The coordinator should download and complete the fillable pdf form, sign [hard or digital signatures are acceptable], and return by email attachment to&nbsp;<a href="mailto:ois@uic.edu" style="background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 18px;">oisexchange@uic.edu</a> with 'Exchange Nomination' in the subject line. UIC does NOT accept self-nominations for exchange.&nbsp;</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Application</span>: </strong>The Office of International
    Services will provide the home institution coordinator and
    student with the UIC Exchange Program Incoming Exchange Nomination &amp;
    Application Directions. This document will explain the application process
    in detail.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Admission</span></strong>: After the
    student submits a completed application to the Office of International
    Services, it is forwarded to the relevant academic department for
    consideration. If the academic department agrees to host the student, UIC
    Admissions will conduct a final review of the application, and, if
    approved, issue the official admission letter.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Deadlines</span></strong>: Nominations and
    applications must be received by the following deadlines to be considered
    for the corresponding study terms. Applications received by the Early
    Action Deadline will receive advanced notification of admission and
    priority consideration for on-campus housing, course selection, and
    immigration document processing.</li>
</ul>

<ul style="margin-top:0in" type="disc">
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l3 level1 lfo4"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Immigration &amp; Visa Requirements</span></strong>:
    After admission to the UIC Exchange Program, students must submit
    documentation so that OIS can issue a Form DS-2019 or Certificate of
    Eligibility for Exchange Visitor Status. The DS-2019 allows the student to
    apply for a J-1 visa at their nearest U.S. Embassy or Consulate.
    Prospective exchange students <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189680"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">can
    read more about the OIS Documents and how to submit them</span></a> on the
    OIS website. Required evidence of funding amounts for exchange students is
    listed in the financial section of this page.<span style="font-size: 12pt; line-height: 115%; color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br>
    <br>
    </span></li>
</ul>
<h2 id="Academics">Academics</h2>
<br>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Exchange students at UIC study
alongside regular UIC students in lectures, classes, discussion groups, labs
and studios. The language of instruction is English and regular attendance and
active participation is expected by the faculty.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0in" type="disc">
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Length of program</span>: </strong>The
    academic calendar at UIC is based on semesters. The fall semester runs
    from August to December, the spring semester runs from January to May. In
    addition, there are two summer sessions, summer session I which runs from
    May to June and summer session II which runs from June to August. Exchange
    students may apply for one or two semesters/sessions.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Learning Agreement</span>: </strong>Prospective
    exchange students should outline their intended field of study and a list
    of desired courses in the Learning Agreement which is included in their
    application to the UIC Exchange Program. This allows the Office of
    International Services to forward the application to the appropriate
    academic department for review. Students and their home institution
    coordinators can refer to the <a href="https://catalog.uic.edu/"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">UIC
    course catalog</span></a> for a list of classes generally offered at UIC.<strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"> </span></strong>Please note that not all courses
    listed in the UIC course catalog will be offered during the exchange
    student&rsquo;s chosen term of study and some courses may be full by the time an
    exchange student arrives on campus and registers for courses. Therefore,
    it is highly recommended that prospective exchange students and home
    institution coordinators remain flexible in this regard and prepare a list
    of courses that includes several options which would be acceptable by the
    home institution. </li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Course Registration</span>: </strong>Exchange
    students will register for courses directly with their hosting academic
    department at UIC. In general, course registration can only be completed
    after the exchange student has arrived in Chicago and completed the <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/students/admitted/check-_in"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">Immigration
    Check-in</span></a> with the Office of International Services. OIS will
    communicate directly with incoming exchange students regarding their
    specific plan for course registration.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Additional Considerations</span></strong>:
    While studying at UIC, exchange students should take at minimum 75% of
    their courses in the field of study indicated on their application.
    Students may take additional courses outside their intended field of study
    at the discretion of their home institution. Please see the Maintaining
    Status section of this page for additional course selection
    considerations.<br>
    <br>
    </li>
</ul>
<h2 id="Financial">Financial</h2>
<br>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Preparing for the financial
aspects of the UIC Exchange Program is important. This includes understanding
responsibilities regarding tuition and fee payment, how to view and pay your
UIC student account, and how much money to budget for living expenses while in
Chicago.</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0in" type="disc">
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Tuition</span></strong>: Exchange students
    pay tuition to their home institution and are not charged UIC tuition
    during their time in the UIC Exchange Program. Please consult your home
    institution coordinator for details on how to pay your tuition bill while
    you are in Chicago.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Fees</span>: </strong>Exchange students are
    charged some UIC fees as outlined in the appendix of the Memorandum of
    Understanding (MOU) between the home school and UIC.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp; </span>For example, most exchange students pay a
    one-time Orientation /Arrival Fee ($149 as of fall 2018) to UIC unless it
    is specifically waived in the MOU.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Student Accounts &amp; Billing</span></strong>:
    Student billing and payment at UIC is handled by University Student
    Financial Services &amp; Cashier Operations. Exchange students can pay for
    applicable fees and <em style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal">CampusCare<strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"> </strong></em>health insurance coverage (if
    not waived by deadline) via the <a href="https://paymybill.uillinois.edu/"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">USFSCO
    website</span></a>. </li>
</ul>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left:.5in"><em style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline; color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">BILLING DISCLAIMER</span></em><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">:
All UIC students, including exchange students, are automatically charged
tuition and all fees upon registering for courses. Exchange students will see
this bill shortly after confirming their course registration - don&rsquo;t panic! OIS
will notify USFSCO to waive tuition and the fees specified by the MOU for each exchange
student. However, there can be a delay between the date USFSCO is notified and
the date the fee waiver is reflected on the exchange student&rsquo;s account.
Exchange students should be mindful of any payment deadlines and communicate
questions about the student bill to OIS in a timely manner.</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0in" type="disc">
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Additional Estimated Expenses</span></strong>:
    In addition to tuition paid to the home institution and fees paid to UIC,
    exchange students should plan funding for additional costs such as living
    expenses and books/supplies. Below are estimates of these expenses based
    on living in Chicago and studying at UIC for one year. These are also the
    amounts exchange students must show as evidence of funding to qualify for
    a DS-2019 form.</li>
</ul>

<p class="MsoNormal"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="font-size: 14pt; line-height: 115%; color: rgb(64, 190, 160);">&nbsp;</span></strong></p>
<h2 id="Housing">Housing</h2>
<br>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Exchange students may choose to
live on-campus with UIC Housing or off-campus in private accommodation. It is
recommended that students select UIC Housing.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
</span>Selecting private off-campus housing could result in unforeseen costs,
unreliable maintenance, difficult commuting and lessened access to university
services.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes"> </span>It is the responsibility of the
exchange student to secure his or her own accommodation as housing is not arranged
by the UIC Exchange Program.</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0in" type="disc">
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l2 level1 lfo2"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">On-Campus Housing</span></strong>: Campus
    Housing provides a variety of convenient, secure, and socially-engaging residence
    halls right on the UIC campus. Exchange students interested in immersing
    themselves in the UIC college experience can visit the <a href="http://housing.uic.edu/"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;
    mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">Campus Housing website</span></a> for more
    information on residence hall options, pricing, and application deadlines.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l2 level1 lfo2"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Off-Campus Housing</span>: </strong>Exchange
    students interested in living off-campus can find resources on the <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189765#off-campus"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">OIS
    website</span></a> and the <a href="https://commuter.uic.edu/housing/"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">Commuter
    Student Resource Center website</span></a>.<br>
    <strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:
    normal"><span style="font-size: 14pt; line-height: 115%; color: rgb(64, 190, 160);"> <br>
    </span></strong></li>
</ul>
<h2 id="HealthInsurance">Health Insurance</h2>
<br>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Exchange students on a J-1 visa
are required to maintain health insurance for the duration of their stay in the
U.S. The level of coverage must meet <a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/text-idx?SID=5e5a8394da71fe43943ca48960218673&amp;mc=true&amp;node=se22.1.62_114&amp;rgn=div8">requirements set by the U.S. Department of State</a>.</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0in" type="disc">
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Campus Care</span>: </strong>Exchange
    students, like all registered UIC students,<strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:
    normal"> </strong>are automatically enrolled in UIC&rsquo;s student health benefit
    program, <em style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal"><a href="https://campuscare.uic.edu/"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:
    Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">CampusCare</span></a></em>. <em style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal">CampusCare</em> provides some, but not
    all, of the health insurance coverage required by the U.S. Department of
    State. Exchange students may choose to stay enrolled in <em style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal">CampusCare </em>and purchase
    supplemental health insurance coverage to meet the DOS requirements.
    Alternatively, exchange students can <a href="http://campuscare.uic.edu/waivers-reinstatement-forms/"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">waive <em style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal">CampusCare</em></span></a> if they are
    able to present evidence of equal or better health insurance coverage.
    Please note that waiving <em style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal">CampusCare </em>coverage
    and corresponding charges must be done directly with <em style="mso-bidi-font-style:
    normal">CampusCare</em> and by their deadlines. Presenting evidence of
    health insurance coverage to OIS during <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189689"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">Immigration
    Check-In</span></a> does not waive <em style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal">CampusCare.</em></li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l4 level1 lfo1"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Private Health Insurance</span></strong>:
    Exchange students may utilize privately-purchased health insurance
    provided that it meets the <a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/text-idx?SID=5e5a8394da71fe43943ca48960218673&amp;mc=true&amp;node=se22.1.62_114&amp;rgn=div8">requirements set by the U.S. Department of    State</a>. To utilize health insurance purchased in your home country,
    documentation must be available in English and submitted through the <em style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal"><a href="http://campuscare.uic.edu/waivers-reinstatement-forms/"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">CampusCare</span><span style="font-style: normal;"> waiver process</span></a></em> and <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189689"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">OIS
    Immigration Check-In</span></a>. </li>
</ul>
<p class="MsoNormal"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="font-size: 14pt; line-height: 115%; color: rgb(64, 190, 160);">&nbsp;</span></strong></p>
<h2 id="Orientation">Orientation</h2>
<br>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">The Office of International
Services hosts International Student Orientation at the beginning of each fall
and spring semester and during the summer sessions. Exchange students should
attend the ISO offered at the beginning of their program at UIC and plan their
arrival to UIC accordingly. Please see the OIS website for <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=213600"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">more
information about International Student Orientation</span></a>.</span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align:center" align="center"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:
normal"><span style="font-size: 14pt; line-height: 115%; color: rgb(64, 190, 160);">&nbsp;</span></strong></p>
<h2 id="MaintainingStatus">Maintaining Status</h2>
<br>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Exchange students enter the U.S.
on a J-1 visa, and therefore, are responsible for maintaining J-1 status for
the duration of their program. Below are some general tips for maintaining J-1
status, however, exchange students are encouraged to <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189669"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">connect
with an OIS Advisor</span></a> regarding any doubts or concerns. Additionally,
maintaining J-1 status is covered during <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=213600"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">International
Student Orientation</span></a>.</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0in" type="disc">
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo3"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Immigration Check-In</span></strong>: Upon
    arrival in Chicago all exchange students must complete an <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189689"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">Immigration
    Check-In with OIS</span></a>. Along with presenting immigration documents,
    exchange students must submit evidence of health insurance coverage that
    is in English and meets the minimum requirements set by the U.S.
    Department of State for the J-1 Exchange Visitor Program.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo3"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Enrollment</span></strong>: J-1 exchange
    students must enroll full-time during the UIC Exchange Program. For
    undergraduate students, full-time at UIC is defined as 12 credits or more
    per semester. For graduate students, full-time is 9 credits or more per
    semester. Additionally, J-1 exchange students are limited in their ability
    to enroll in online courses. Please see the OIS website for <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189693"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">more
    information about full-time enrollment requirements</span></a>.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo3"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Employment</span>: </strong>J-1 visas are
    first and foremost student visas. Therefore, regulations surrounding J-1
    employment are strict and the consequences for violating them can be
    severe. <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=386240"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">Information
    about J-1 employment</span></a> can be found on the OIS website. However,
    please <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189669"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">consult
    with an OIS Advisor</span></a> prior to participating in any work or
    training activity, paid or unpaid.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp; </span></li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo3"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Address Updates</span></strong>: J-1
    exchange students must maintain a current local (U.S.) and permanent
    (international) address at all times. Exchange students should <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189697"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">report
    address changes to OIS</span></a> within ten days.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo3"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Travel</span></strong>: J-1 exchange
    students who wish to travel outside the U.S. during their UIC Exchange
    Program should confirm that they have valid immigration documents,
    including an updated DS-2019 travel signature, prior to departure. More
    information about travel and how to update a travel signature can be found
    on the <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189695"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">OIS
    website</span></a>. </li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo3"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Departure</span></strong>: J-1 exchange
    students have a 30 day grace period after the program end date listed on
    their DS-2019 during which they may remain in the U.S. to travel or
    prepare for departure. Work, study, and re-entry to the U.S. are not
    permitted during the 30 day grace period. More information about departure
    procedures, including how to formally notify OIS or your departure, can be
    found on the <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189699"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">OIS
    website</span></a>.<br>
    <br>
    </li>
</ul>
<h2 id="GettingInvolved">Getting Involved</h2>
<br>
<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="color: rgb(127, 127, 127);">Cultural exchange is at the
heart of the J-1 Exchange Visitor Program. Participants in the UIC Exchange
Program are encouraged to get involved on-campus so that they can interact with
UIC students, share their home culture and learn about U.S. culture. Below are
just some of the opportunities for involvement available at UIC.</span></p>
<ul style="margin-top:0in" type="disc">
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo5"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">OIS Programs &amp; Events</span></strong>:
    The Office of International Services hosts a variety of cultural and
    social programs throughout the academic year. The majority of these
    programs are free of cost to exchange students and provide an opportunity
    to connect with the broader UIC international community. For a list of
    upcoming OIS programs and events, please see the <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189740"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">OIS
    website</span></a>.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo5"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Trade Winds</span></strong>: One of OIS&rsquo;
    signature programs, Trade Winds, is and intercultural friendship program
    in which international students and U.S. students are placed in small
    groups and encouraged throughout the semester to educate each other about
    their cultures, countries, perspectives and life experiences. Trade Winds
    is a fantastic opportunity for exchange students to build meaningful
    intercultural relationships in their short time at UIC. Learn more on the <a href="https://www.ois.uic.edu/cms/One.aspx?portalId=1581&amp;pageId=189741"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">OIS
    website</span></a>.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo5"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Center for Student Involvement</span></strong>:
    UIC has a vibrant student community and the Center for Student Involvement
    organizes programming for students throughout the year. <a href="http://campusprograms.uic.edu/"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:
    Calibri;mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">Check out their website</span></a>
    for upcoming events and a list of student organizations to join.</li>
    <li class="MsoNormal" style="color:#7F7F7F;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo5"><strong style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Campus Recreation</span></strong>: Exchange
    students who are interested in athletics can visit the <a href="http://recreation.uic.edu/"><span style="mso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;
    mso-hansi-font-family:Calibri">UIC Campus Recreation website</span></a>
    for information on their work out facilities, sports clubs, and intramural
    sports leagues and tournaments.</li>
</ul></div>
